considers the cost of p rovidin g Medicaid t o members who w ork a t an employer which e mployed 50 o r more e mployees for State Fisca l Year (SFY) 20 18. This r eport was c reated t o meet the requirements s et forth in Senate Bill 366. S enate B ill 366 r equires "... th e Department of H ealth and Human S ervices t o prepare an an nual report w hich lis ts all employers in t his S tate w hich h ave 50 or more employees and the number of full -time employees of such an employer who are enrolled in Medicaid." Technical Notes Throughout this report employment was defined using the wage threshold associated with earning minimum wage in Nevada. More spe cifically, the group of Medicaid members presented below represents employee s who earned $3,480.00 or more in gross wage earnings for a 12 -week consecutive period (one quarter) as reported to the Department of Employment, Training, and Rehabilitation. This gross quarterly wage represents the minimum wage of $7.25 an hour paid to employees who work for employers who offer health coverage benefits and who worked 40 hours a week. De termining wh ether or not an employer offered health coverage benefits was d one by matching the employer's Employer Identification N umber (EIN) against the Department of Labor's Employee Benefits Security Administration's database of Form 5500's filed by the employer. Form 5500 identifies the different welfare, health, and pension plans offered by an employer. A Schedule 4a filed as part of the Form 5500 indicates that the employer offers a health benefits plan or an employee welfare plan. However, not all employers need to file a Form 5500 and may offer health benefits to their emp loyees. The Division of Insurance does not currently track which employers offer health insurance unless there is a consumer complaint. Determining if a company had employees on Medicaid was done by matching Medicaid members to records in the Department of Employment, Training, and Rehabilitation (DETR). This match provided quarterly wage information and the identification number of the employer that the Medicaid member worked for during each quarter of SFY 2018 . A Medicaid member may have had more than on e employer during the course of the year. DETR also supplied a file with the identification number, company name, and address for employers in Nevada with 50 or more employees. The wage file and employer file were then combined to identify which Medicaid members were employed by companies with 50 or more employees . To determine dependents of Medicaid members who work for a company with 50 or more employees, the list of Medicaid members who work for companies with 50 or more employees was matched against Medicaid enrollment . A dependent was defined as the person who is the head of household of an employee, the spouse of an employee, a child of an employee or the head of household, or an unborn child of an employee or head of household. 1 The Bureau of Labor Statistics, Occupational Employment Statistics, May 2017 State Occupational Employment and Wage Estimates - Nevada, https://www.bls.gov/oes/current/oes_nv.htm#00 -0000 4 of 76Results There were 105,895 Medicaid members employed by employers with 50 or more employees and an additional 123,164 dependents. T he total cost of providing healthcare to the se employees was approximately $375,098,269. The total cost for providing healthcare to the dependents of these employees was approximately $ 263,465,532. Combining these costs, the overall cost of healthcare to these Medicaid members was $ 638,563,801. The average comp any with 50 or more total employees and with employees on Medicaid had 26 employees on Medicaid and 30 dependents associated with these employees on Medicaid, with the average cost to Nevada Medicaid of $157, 282. The table below displays the companies with 50 or more employees who made up the top ten employers with employees and dependents on Medicaid when ranked by the number of employees and dependents on Nev ada Medicaid. Thirty -five percent (35%) were Caucasian, 31% were Hispanic, 24% were African American, and 10% were of another race/ethnicity. Twenty -eight percent (28 %) were Caucasian, 38% were Hispanic, 23% were African American, and 11 % were of another race/ethnicity. Language information was unknown for the majority of the dependents (63%). Thirty -five percent (35%) spoke English as a primary language , and 2 % listed Spanish as their language spoken. Thirty -seven percent (3 7%) of the dependents were 0-5 years old, 49 % were 6-17 years old, and 14 % were 18 years old or older. There were no dependents aged 65 or older. An additional 9 % were eligible under Adult Expansion, 6 % were eligible under CHIP to Medicaid, and 5 % were eligible under Nevada Check -up. Median Wage Subset It may also be of interest to consider the subset of these employees who earned enough in wages to meet the quarterly wage threshold associated with the median Nevada wage. More specifically, the subset of these Medicaid members who e arned $8, 059.20 or more in gross earnings in a quarter. This gross quarterly wage represents the median wage in Nevada in 2016, of $16.79 an hour. Ou t of the 105,895 Medicaid members employed by employers with 50 or more employees who earned $3,480.00 or more, 18,720 Medicaid members (18%) earned $8, 059.20 or more in gross earnings in a quarter. There were also 32,964 dependents associated with the Medicaid members in this subset . The demographics associated with this subset did not differ significantly from the demographics of the larger pool of Medicaid members and dependents considered in this report. *Budget Categories that are not displayed here made up less than 1% of this caseload . These include Aged, Blind, and Disabled, Waiver, County Match, Child Welfare, and Child Welfare - State Only.
